+# Why CVE-2026-41071 Does Not Affect `libheif` 1.11.0 on Debian Bullseye
+
+## CVE-2026-41071 – Heap Buffer Over-Read via Unvalidated Sample Count in `SampleAuxInfoReader`
+
+- **Component:** `SampleAuxInfoReader` constructor (HEIF sequences-track parsing)
+- **CWE:** CWE-125 (Out-of-bounds Read)
+- **Issue:** The constructor iterates over `saiz->get_num_samples()` samples without validating that the count is consistent with the number of entries in the track's `chunks` vector. A crafted sequence file whose `saiz` box declares more samples than the chunk table covers advances `current_chunk` past `chunks.size()`, causing an out-of-bounds read. Triggered purely during file parsing (`heif_context_read_from_file`), with no user interaction.
+- **Fix Commit:** `f20c81745e917b4c496615140385c86d7a2fa58d`
+- **Upstream Status:** Fixed in upstream `libheif` 1.22.0
+
+---
+
+## Why Debian Bullseye (`libheif` 1.11.0-1+deb11u2) Is NOT Affected
+
+The vulnerability lives in the **sequences-track** subsystem — `SampleAuxInfoReader`, the `saiz` / `saio` auxiliary-information boxes, and the track-level `chunks` table. This entire subsystem was **added to `libheif` years after v1.11.0** and does not exist in this version.
+
+### Root Cause Analysis
+
+The vulnerable loop in the `SampleAuxInfoReader` constructor walks `saiz->get_num_samples()` samples and increments `current_chunk` without bounding it against `chunks.size()`. The upstream fix (v1.22.0, commit `f20c81745e917b4c496615140385c86d7a2fa58d`) adds the missing bounds check so the loop cannot advance past the end of the `chunks` vector.
+
+In v1.11.0, **none of this code exists**:
+
+- `SampleAuxInfoReader` and the sequences/track parsing subsystem were first introduced upstream and released in **v1.20.0**.
+- There is no `saiz` / `saio` box handling, no `SampleAuxInfoReader` class, no `get_num_samples()` accessor, and no track-level `chunks` vector in v1.11.0.
+
+> Note: v1.11.0 contains unrelated identifiers that superficially resemble the CVE wording — the public API `heif_image_get_data_chunk()` (pixel-data chunks of a single decoded image) and a code comment mentioning "image sequences" brands (`heif_hevc`, `heif_hevx`). Neither relates to a track's sample/chunk table or to `saiz` parsing; they are not the vulnerable code.
+
+### Version Comparison
+
+| Version | File | `SampleAuxInfoReader` present? | Unvalidated sample loop? | Affected? |
+|----------|------|--------------------------------|--------------------------|-----------|
+| v1.11.0 (Bullseye) | (none — subsystem absent) | NO | NO | NO |
+| v1.20.0 – v1.21.2 (pre-fix) | sequences-track sources | YES | YES | YES |
+| v1.22.0 (post-fix) | sequences-track sources | YES | bounds-checked | NO |
+
+### Debian Bullseye Package Details
+
+| Field | Value |
+|-------|-------|
+| Package | libheif |
+| Version | 1.11.0-1+deb11u2 |
+| Distribution | Debian 11 (Bullseye) |
+| Upstream Version | 1.11.0 |
+| Status | **NOT AFFECTED** |
+
+---
+
+## Why the Fix Cannot Be Applied
+
+The upstream fix modifies the sequences-track parsing sources. On v1.11.0 this patch:
+
+- **Cannot apply** — the `SampleAuxInfoReader` class, the `saiz` / `saio` box handlers, and the track `chunks` vector do not exist.
+- **Is not needed** — there is no equivalent sample-auxiliary-info parsing path elsewhere in v1.11.0, so there is no unbounded loop to fix.
+
+### Verification
+
+The first check below returns empty on the v1.11.0 source tree, confirming the vulnerable code is absent; the others match only the unrelated identifiers noted above:
+
+```bash
+grep -rn "SampleAuxInfoReader\|saiz\|saio\|get_num_samples" libheif/   # (empty)
+grep -rn "chunk" libheif/heif.cc        # only heif_image_get_data_chunk (per-image pixel data)
+grep -rn "sequences" libheif/heif.h     # only "// brands for image sequences" comment
+````
+
+---
+
+## Summary
+
+* CVE-2026-41071 affects the sequences-track `SampleAuxInfoReader` subsystem, introduced in v1.20.0
+* That subsystem does not exist in v1.11.0 — no `saiz` / `saio` parsing, no `SampleAuxInfoReader`, no track `chunks` table
+* Debian Bullseye's `libheif` 1.11.0-1+deb11u2 is **NOT AFFECTED**
+* No patch is required; the upstream fix cannot even be applied because the target code does not exist
+
+**Status: NOT_AFFECTED — No action needed.**
