+# Why CVE-2025-68431 Does Not Affect `libheif` 1.11.0 on Debian Bullseye
+
+## Overview: What Is `libheif`?
+
+`libheif` is an open-source library for reading and writing HEIF (High Efficiency Image File Format) and AVIF images. It provides:
+
+- HEIF/HEIC image decoding and encoding
+- AVIF image support
+- Overlay image composition
+- Thumbnail extraction
+
+The library is maintained at https://github.com/strukturag/libheif and is packaged across multiple Linux distributions.
+
+---
+
+## CVE-2025-68431 – Heap Buffer Over-Read via Integer Underflow in Overlay Processing
+
+- **Component:** `HeifPixelImage::overlay()` function
+- **CWE:** CWE-125 (Out-of-bounds Read), CWE-190 (Integer Overflow/Underflow)
+- **Issue:** Incorrect `memcpy` size calculation using `in_w - in_x0` when `in_w` has already been pre-adjusted by `in_x0`, causing a double subtraction that underflows
+- **Fix Commit:** `b8c12a7b70f46c9516711a988483bed377b78d46`
+- **Upstream Status:** Fixed in upstream `libheif` (post v1.21.0)
+
+---
+
+## Why Debian Bullseye (`libheif` 1.11.0-1+deb11u2) Is NOT Affected
+
+The vulnerability is a **regression** introduced during code refactoring between v1.11.0 and v1.21.0. The bug does not exist in v1.11.0.
+
+### Root Cause Analysis
+
+The fix commit changes line 1511 in `libheif/pixelimage.cc` (renamed from `heif_image.cc` in later versions):
+
+```cpp
+- memcpy(..., in_w - in_x0);  // vulnerable in v1.21.0
++ memcpy(..., in_w);           // fixed
+```
+
+In v1.21.0 (pre-fix), `in_w` is pre-adjusted at line 1485:
+
+```cpp
+in_w = in_w - in_x0;  // pre-adjustment added during refactoring
+```
+
+This makes `in_w - in_x0` at the `memcpy` a **double subtraction**, causing integer underflow.
+
+In v1.11.0, this pre-adjustment **does not exist**. The variable `in_w` retains its original value (the full overlay width), making `in_w - in_x0` the **correct and only** subtraction.
+
+### Version Comparison
+
+| Version | File | `in_w` pre-adjusted? | `memcpy` size | Correct? |
+|----------|------|----------------------|---------------|----------|
+| v1.11.0 (Bullseye) | `heif_image.cc` | NO | `in_w - in_x0` | YES |
+| v1.21.0 (pre-fix) | `pixelimage.cc` | YES (line 1485) | `in_w - in_x0` | NO (double subtraction) |
+| v1.21.0 (post-fix) | `pixelimage.cc` | YES (line 1485) | `in_w` | YES |
+
+### Debian Bullseye Package Details
+
+| Field | Value |
+|---------|---------|
+| Package | libheif |
+| Version | 1.11.0-1+deb11u2 |
+| Distribution | Debian 11 (Bullseye) |
+| Upstream Version | 1.11.0 |
+| Status | **NOT AFFECTED** |
+
+---
+
+## Why Applying the Fix Would Be Harmful
+
+Applying the upstream fix (changing `in_w - in_x0` to `in_w`) on v1.11.0 would:
+
+- **Remove a necessary subtraction**, since `in_w` is NOT pre-adjusted in this version
+- **Cause `memcpy` to copy `in_x0` extra bytes** beyond the intended region
+- **Introduce a heap buffer overflow** — the exact opposite of the intended security improvement
+
+---
+
+## Summary
+
+- CVE-2025-68431 is a regression introduced in later versions of `libheif` during refactoring
+- The vulnerable code pattern (`in_w` pre-adjustment + `in_w - in_x0` double subtraction) does not exist in v1.11.0
+- Debian Bullseye's `libheif` 1.11.0-1+deb11u2 is **NOT AFFECTED**
+- No patch is required; applying the upstream fix would **introduce a new vulnerability**
+
+**Status: NOT_AFFECTED — No action needed.**
+
+---
